{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17587112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17587112"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:41:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:41:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15120"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15120"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7808"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62727"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7808"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15120"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48175"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"878"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"9339"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19039"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19042"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20426"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62727"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of intermittent chest pain and difficulty swallowing both solids and liquids.. A barium swallow is conducted and shows a \u0027corkscrew\u0027 appearance of the oesophagus. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nutcracker oesophagus","Diffuse oesophageal spasm","Achalasia","Scleroderma","Oesophageal web"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of intermittent chest pain and dysphagia, combined with the characteristic \u0027corkscrew\u0027 appearance on barium swallow, is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Ediffuse oesophageal spasm\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is characterised by uncoordinated, simultaneous contractions of the oesophagus that can cause both chest pain and difficulty swallowing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENutcracker oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by high-amplitude peristaltic contractions but maintains normal peristaltic sequence. Gastro-oesophageal reflux is an important trigger for this condition. The barium swallow typically appears normal, other than during an episode, where the patient may have severe chest pain. (Image 1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchalasia\u003C/strong\u003E presents with progressive dysphagia to both solids and liquids, but typically shows a dilated oesophagus with a \u0027bird\u0027s beak\u0027 appearance on barium swallow due to failure of lower oesophageal sphincter relaxation (Image 2). Chest pain is less common than in diffuse oesophageal spasm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScleroderma\u003C/strong\u003E affects the oesophagus in many patients but typically presents with reflux symptoms and shows a dilated, atonic oesophagus on imaging (Image 3). It would also be accompanied by other systemic features of scleroderma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal webs\u003C/strong\u003E are thin membranes of tissue that protrude into the oesophageal lumen, typically appearing as a thin indentation on barium swallow. They do not cause the corkscrew appearance seen in this case (Image 4).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of diffuse oesophageal spasm is typically confirmed with oesophageal manometry, which would show simultaneous, uncoordinated contractions. Treatment options include calcium channel blockers, nitrates, and in severe cases, surgical myotomy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diffuse oesophageal spasm is characterised by uncoordinated, simultaneous contractions of the oesophagus causing chest pain and dysphagia.","The \u0027corkscrew\u0027 or \u0027rosary bead\u0027 appearance on barium swallow is characteristic of diffuse oesophageal spasm.","Diffuse oesophageal spasm must be differentiated from other motility disorders including achalasia and nutcracker oesophagus."],"references":["Goel S, Nookala V. Diffuse Esophageal Spasm. 2023 Jul 2. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31082150.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48175"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15120"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21186"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21187"},{"type":"media","id":"21188"},{"type":"media","id":"21190"},{"type":"media","id":"21191"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21186"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/AAJwHYdfvD9dslR8hThuhgORUdSp0B.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/AAJwHYdfvD9dslR8hThuhgORUdSp0B.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":593}},{"type":"media","id":"21187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21187"},"attributes":{"m